'''Frank Gordon Thorpe''', {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|CMG|MBE}} (15 February 1885 – 30 March 1967) was a senior Australian public servant. He was Public Service Commissioner between 1936 and 1947.

==Life and career==
Frank Thorpe was born on 15 February 1885 in Kooreh, Victoria.<ref name=Calaby>{{citation|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/thorpe-frank-gordon-11856|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428093856/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/thorpe-frank-gordon-11856|archivedate=28 April 2014|deadurl=no|title=Thorpe, Frank Gordon (1885–1967)|first=Matthew|last=Calaby|publisher=Australian National University|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography}}</ref>

Thorpe started his [[Australian Public Service|Commonwealth Public Service]] career in 1901, one of the Australia's earliest Commonwealth public servants, appointed as a personal clerk to the deputy Postmaster General in the [[Postmaster-General's Department]].<ref name=Calaby/>
When Thorpe volunteered to serve in World War I, he was rejected and instead selected for temporary duty at the [[Department of Defence (1901–1921)|Department of Defence]].<ref name=Appointment>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2423773|newspaper=The Canberra Times|page=2|date=10 February 1937|title=Mr. F.G. Thorpe: P.S. Commissioner Cabinet Appointment}}</ref>

In 1921 he joined the [[Prime Minister's Department (Australia)|Prime Minister's Department]] as a senior clerk.<ref name=Calaby/>

Thorpe moved to the Commonwealth Public Service Board in 1923, appointed as an assistant-inspector.<ref name=Calaby/> He was appointed Public Service Commissioner in 1937.<ref name=Appointment/> He continued working as Commissioner of the Board throughout World War II, including during periods of increasing pressure.<ref name=Calaby/>

Thorpe retired in 1947 after 49 years in the public service.<ref>{{citation|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article22416866|title=Personal Paragraphs|date=25 March 1947|newspaper=The Argus|page=2}}</ref> His farewell function was presided over by [[Stuart McFarlane]], then [[Departmental secretary|Secretary]] of the [[Department of the Treasury (Australia)|Treasury]] and more than 110 senior public servants attended.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2710738|title=Mr. F.G. Thorpe Farewelled By Public Servants|newspaper=The Canberra Times|page=2|date=25 March 1947}}</ref>

After retirement, Thorpe was appointed Chairman of the Overseas Telecommunications Commission Promotions Appeal Board for two years from 1953.<ref name="NAA">{{citation|title=CP 275: Frank Gordon THORPE CMG, MBE|url=http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/SearchOld.asp?Number=CP+275|publisher=National Archives of Australia|accessdate=12 September 2014}}</ref>

Thorpe died in Canberra in 1967.<ref name=Calaby/>

==Awards==
In June&nbsp;1936, Thorpe was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1086562&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428093548/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1086562&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archivedate=28 April 2014|title=Search Australian Honours: THORPE, Frank Gordon|publisher=Australian Government|work=itsanhonour.gov.au}}</ref> He was made a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] in June&nbsp;1939 whilst he was serving as Chairman of the Public Service Board.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1066719&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428094539/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1066719&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archivedate=28 April 2014|title=Search Australian Honours: THORPE, Frank Gordon|publisher=Australian Government|work=itsanhonour.gov.au}}</ref>

